    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Pieter Nanninck to Miklós Oláh (Leuven, 5 October 1537)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">Although Ludolphus, who has arrived with Rutger Pathius,
                            has not brought any letter, he has reported that Oláh is well. Nanninck
                            is suffering from his eye disease, he inherited trouble from two poets:
                            Virgil had headaches, while Horace had eye infections. He has taken on
                            Pathius’ brother as a convivial fellow, but in a way that Nanninck’s
                            brother is feeding him and Nanninck is teaching him, this way they
                            divide worry and profit between them. Both Oláh and the Queen trust
                            Pathius so much that they do not need to worry they will be
                            disappointed; but he does not want Pathius to learn that Nanninck’s
                            brother had his doubts. He cannot write more now due to his grief, he
                            has lost his sister.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb facs="https://www.eleveltar.hu/kereso-portlet/spring/digitalcontent/getcontent/preservica/AC8C8C63-2C8C-4AB9-AD0C-7765B5D797B2
                    "/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Idem Nicolao Olao salutem plurimam. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">Etsi nihil litterarum ad me attulit
                        <persName>Ludolphus</persName><note xml:id="note.1">He was probably a
                        protégé of Oláh, see <hi rend="smallcap">Polet</hi> 1936, 259.</note>
                    noster, qui huc cum <persName>fratre</persName><note xml:id="note.2">See Ep.
                        590. Cap.
                        2.<ref>olahus.tei.15370928_1</ref></note><persName>Rutgeri</persName><note
                        xml:id="note.3">Rutger Pathius.</note> venit, tamen quia mihi <milestone
                            unit="pb" facs="https://www.eleveltar.hu/kereso-portlet/spring/digitalcontent/getcontent/preservica/D56DB27D-57EE-41DB-AF96-5137CAA17304
                            "/>te recte valere nuntiavit, multisque negotiis impeditum esse, cur
                    minus scriberes, statui mollius mihi ferendum esse desiderium tuarum litterarum,
                    quod tum lenies, ubi tua negotia permiserint. Nos cum medicis diu luctati sumus
                    adversus lippitudinem,<note xml:id="note.4">See Ep.
                            583.<ref>olahus.tei.15370310_1</ref></note> quam tamen in hoc genere
                    mali rectius ὀφθαλμίαν<note xml:id="note.5">‘eye disease’.</note> vocavero. Duo
                    summi poetae sua vitia in me exonerarunt: <persName>Vergilius</persName> capitis
                    dolorem, <persName>Horatius</persName> lippitudinem, mallem potius virtutes
                    transtulissent ἀλλὰ τὰ παρόντα <choice>
                        <orig>ἐὐ</orig>
                        <supplied>εὖ</supplied>
                    </choice> τίθεσθαι δεῖ.<note xml:id="note.6">‘but the current things have to be
                        settled’.</note> Ego
                        <persName>fratrem</persName><persName>Rutgeri</persName> tui in
                        ὁμοτράπεζον<note xml:id="note.7">‘convivial fellow’.</note> accepi, quamquam
                    alendi negotium in <persName>fratrem meum</persName><note xml:id="note.8">We do
                        not know his name, but according to Nanninck, he later entered the service
                        of Emperor Charles V and settled in Ghent. Nanninck reports in 1548 that his
                        brother had been the victim of a night attack at the Imperial Court and
                        killed one of his assailants but he was released thanks to the intercession
                        of his powerful friends and the Hague Senate, see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Polet</hi> 1936, 3.</note> transtuli, docendi mihi reservavi, ita inter
                    nos cura et lucrum partitur; is, ut est sollicitus, praesertim in nova familia
                    rogavit ex me, numquid periculi in posterum foret de solutione; respondi omnia
                    secura esse. Talem esse <persName>Rutgerum</persName>, et in tanta gratia apud
                    reginam, ut nihil tale de eo metuendum sit, deinde tui apud eum tanta
                    reverentia, ut etiam si talis non esset, qualis quam maxime est, te tamen salvo,
                    nunquam illum ausurum solutionem differre, tantum abesse, ut omitteret, deinde
                    ipsum iuvenem verbis tuis mihi commendatum, idque me scire ex litteris
                        <persName>Dani</persName>,<note xml:id="note.9">Jakob Jespersen.</note> si
                    modo ea scripsit ex tuo mandato. Nolim tamen has fratris mei haesitationes
                        <persName>Rutgero</persName> indices, scio enim eum stulta sollicitudine
                    moveri, teque mihi ultro indicaturum, si quid in hoc nomine periculi esset, quod
                    ego nullum omnino arbitror. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.3">Nos maluimus pauca, quam nihil scribere, ne aut opportunitate
                    <milestone unit="pb" facs="https://www.eleveltar.hu/kereso-portlet/spring/digitalcontent/getcontent/preservica/199ED6B2-310C-422A-813B-353BF77839C0
                        "/>tabellarii non uterer, aut loquacitate tuas hoc
                    tempore gravissimas occupationes accumularem, deinde luctus, in quo nunc sum,
                    amisi enim unicam <persName>sororem</persName>,<note xml:id="note.10"
                        >Marguerite, wife of Jordan van Foreest, died in September 1537, see <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Polet</hi> 1936, 3.</note> vix mihi permittit ullum usum
                    litterarum, cuius causa brevi in <placeName>Hollandiam</placeName> propero. Tu,
                    mi Unice et Doctissime et Humanissime Patrone, diu nobis studiisque feliciter
                    vivas. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.4">3. Nonas Octobres 1537.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
